	of two different approaches for the reduction of a set of diatomic
	molecule data to a compact set of parameters defining a potential
	energy curve and Born-Oppenheimer breakdown (BOB) radial functions.
	This paper explains the apparent discrepancies between an algebraic
	method championed by J.F. Ogilvie and a numerical method pioneered
	by J.A. Coxon. It confirms the validity of the central underlying
	assumption of both approaches, namely, that spectroscopic data for
	one or multiple isotopomers can be reduced accurately to a compact
	set of parameters characterizing the potential energy and BOB radial
